<div </div
&nbsp;
That is why the American president invited Tehran not to attack. In the midst of these tensions, India, Canada, Germany, the United Kingdom, Poland, France and Austria and Italy have asked their citizens not to go to the region or leave it, while the Lufthansa airline suspended its flights to Iran. For twenty-four hours, which coincide with the beginning of the long holiday weekend for the end of Ramadan, the Iranian authorities do not echo threats against Israel. In his Friday prayer, for example, the imam of Tehran Kazem Seddiqi dedicated his words to the war in Gaza and to the "Palestinian resistance".
In recent days, diplomatic activity was intense with talks between Iran's Foreign Minister, Hosein Amir Abdolahian, and his counterparts in the United Kingdom, Australia, Germany and yesterday, also with Antonio Tajani. In the talks Abdolahian expressed his dissatisfaction with the UN Security Council to condemn the attack on the consulate and reiterated the right of his country to self-defense. &nbsp;
Western diplomats, for their part, asked Tehran moderation. "I urged Tehran to act in moderation", wrote on X the Italian Foreign Minister who today, on the margin of an event in Milan, reiterated that in the Middle East "the risks of an escalation are there" and "would be concerned to protect the Italian soldiers who are at the border between Lebanon and Israel" as well as "insistries on the need to guarantee the merchant traffic through Suez and the Red Sea and receive insurance that "non-arms".
The calls for moderation were rejected by Tehran through the issuer Nournews, linked to the Supreme National Security Council of Iran, who warned against the demands of "moderation" by the West.
<div </div
&nbsp;
"Iran has learned from its political ties to the West that it should always be skeptical about its demands for self-control and moderation," reads on the X account of the broadcaster. On the other hand, next Monday Abdolahian will participate in a session of the Commission for National Security and Foreign Policy of the Iranian parliament to discuss a "potential" retaliation against Israel, the Iranian media today reported. "The Iranian regime is pleased with the panic in Israel," says Analyst Ali Alfoneh, " patiently awaits the moment and the goal may not be even in the Middle East," wrote today the Arabic Gulf States Institute in Washington.
Meanwhile, life develops normally in Iran. In recent days public places such as parks filled with families who took advantage of the festive weekend for the end of Ramadan. In Mellat Park, in the north of the capital, outdoor concerts were held this weekend. Today, the first working day of the Iranian week, the city presented the usual traffic jams of people directed at work. Such is the normality that the Iranian police warned that it will intensify measures to reintroduce the mandatory use of the Islamic veil from this Saturday, which many women in the country have stopped doing after the death of Mahsa Amini.
