AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp; High levels of post-traumatic stress disorder, or PTSD, and general anxiety among refugees and displaced persons in Ukraine. It reveals a study conducted by researchers at the International Blast Injury Research Network of the University of Southampton, published on PLOS Global Public Health. Scientists conducted an investigation to understand how the mental health of Ukrainian displaced persons was influenced by the ongoing war. Since the beginning of the Russian invasion of Ukraine in February 2022, at least 13 million people have been forced to leave their homes. Both exposure to war and evacuation, in particular loss of community, housing and economic resources, affect mental health. These effects tend to be amplified among the elderly, people taking care of children and vulnerable populations. Between April and July 2022, researchers interviewed over 8,000 participants, all refugees or displaced persons in Ukraine. Participants answered questions about their current situation, their mental health and their exposure to explosions caused by bombs or other military actions.
&nbsp;
Almost 8 out of 10 participants, who remained in Ukraine, and more than half of the refugees reported being exposed to explosions. Almost 70% of all survey participants reported that they were anxious, with people remaining in Ukraine who reported more frequent anxiety and flashbacks of traumatic events than refugees. Flashbacks are a PTSD symptom and may vary from elusive and intrusive memories to episodes of a few minutes when you feel like reliving traumatic events; in this study, the frequency of flashbacks was related to exposure to explosion. Overall, the study suggests that displaced persons remaining in Ukraine have worse mental health results than refugees; which probably because of the continued exposure to war. However, refugees still face considerable mental health problems. "Mental health and psychosocial support must be considered a priority in humanitarian aid," said researchers.
&nbsp;
"The exposure to explosion events can be incredibly distressing," the authors added. Our survey of 8300 Ukrainian respondents shows that almost 70% reported witnessing an explosion during the first 4 months of Russia's large-scale invasion in 2022.
"The most worrying aspect is that many respondents exposed to explosions reported negative mental health outcomes, including PTSD symptoms," concluded scientists.&nbsp;
